= 0.932).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4208AA0F36672268FF23FDED86CCFD18" blockId="25.[212,1171,503,654]" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567">
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE36672268FF23FDED859FFDD9" author="Ackery PR &amp; Smith CR &amp; Vane-Wright RI" box="[254,500,567,591]" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" refId="ref24360" refString="Ackery PR, Smith CR, Vane-Wright RI, editors. 1995. Carcasson' s African butterflies: an annotated catalogue of the Papilionoidea and Hesperioidea of the Afrotropical Region. East Melbourne (Australia): CSIRO." type="book" year="1995">Ackery et al. (1995)</bibRefCitation>
accepted the former division of this species into three subspecies, but 
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE36672268FE5AFD8D8651FDF9" author="Kielland J" box="[391,570,599,623]" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" refId="ref25501" refString="Kielland J. 1990. Butterflies of Tanzania. Melbourne: Hill House." type="book" year="1990">Kielland (1990)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE36672268FD97FD8D8683FDF9" author="Larsen TB" box="[586,744,599,623]" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" refId="ref25550" refString="Larsen TB. 1996. The butterflies of Kenya and their natural history. 2 nd edn. Oxford (UK): Oxford University Press." type="book" year="1996">Larsen (1996)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE36672268FCFBFD8D87B7FDF9" author="D' Abrera B" box="[806,988,599,623]" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" refId="ref25233" refString="D' Abrera B. 1997. Butterflies of the Afrotropical Region (2 nd edn). Part I. Papilionidae, Pieridae, Acraeidae, Danaidae &amp; Satyridae. Melbourne: Hill House." type="book" year="1997">d’ Abrera (1997)</bibRefCitation>
all rejected this arrangement, and it is not followed here.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4208AA0F36672268FF09FD6D8000FC7B" blockId="25.[212,1172,694,1229]" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567">
<emphasis id="70C3761D36672268FF09FD6D855EFD59" box="[212,309,695,719]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567">Records.</emphasis>
According to 
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE36672268FE39FD6C86E4FD58" author="Kielland J" box="[484,655,694,718]" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" refId="ref25501" refString="Kielland J. 1990. Butterflies of Tanzania. Melbourne: Hill House." type="book" year="1990">Kielland (1990</bibRefCitation>
, p.61), found in most parts of 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F36672268FBD5FD6C801AFD58" box="[1032,1137,694,718]" name="Tanzania" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
at altitudes from near sea level to 
<quantity id="854F07EA36672268FD93FD0C86CCFD78" box="[590,679,726,750]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" unit="m" value="2100.0">2100 m</quantity>
, it has since been recorded at 
<quantity id="854F07EA36672268FBC8FD0C8000FD78" box="[1045,1131,726,750]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" unit="m" value="3000.0">3000 m</quantity>
on 
<collectingRegion id="807364ED36672268FF09FD2C85DCFC98" box="[212,439,758,782]" country="Tanzania" name="Kilimanjaro" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567">Mount Kilimanjaro</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE36672268FE17FD2C863BFC98" author="Liseki SD" box="[458,592,758,782]" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" refId="ref25599" refString="Liseki SD. 2009. Butterfly diversity and its relevance to conservation in north-eastern Tanzania [PhD thesis). Canterbury (UK): University of Kent." type="book" year="2009">Liseki 2009</bibRefCitation>
). The BMNH collection includes 
<specimenCount id="54B1618636672268FC3EFD2C8035FC98" box="[995,1118,758,782]" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" type="male">four males</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount id="54B1618636672268FF09FCCC8537FCB8" box="[212,348,790,814]" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" type="female">five females</specimenCount>
from 
<collectingRegion id="807364ED36672268FE71FCCC865DFCB8" box="[428,566,790,814]" country="Tanzania" name="Kilimanjaro" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567">Kilimanjaro</collectingRegion>
(including two from Loitokitok), one of the males having been collected in W. 
<collectingRegion id="807364ED36672268FDFEFCEC86C6FCD8" box="[547,685,822,846]" country="Tanzania" name="Kilimanjaro" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567">Kilimanjaro</collectingRegion>
at 
<quantity id="854F07EA36672268FD05FCEC8742FCD8" box="[728,809,822,846]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.524" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" unit="ft" value="5000.0">5000 ft</quantity>
(Cooper). At times a common butterfly, irregular and relatively minor migrations are known to occur (
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE36672268FC27FC8C80EFFCF8" author="Larsen TB" box="[1018,1156,854,878]" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" refId="ref25550" refString="Larsen TB. 1996. The butterflies of Kenya and their natural history. 2 nd edn. Oxford (UK): Oxford University Press." type="book" year="1996">Larsen 1996</bibRefCitation>
). Seasonally very variable, with distinct wet-season and dry-season forms (
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE36672268FBECFCAC8562FC38" author="Kielland J" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" refId="ref25501" refString="Kielland J. 1990. Butterflies of Tanzania. Melbourne: Hill House." type="book" year="1990">Kielland 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE36672268FEFEFC4C8664FC38" author="Pringle ELL &amp; Henning GA &amp; Ball JB" box="[291,527,918,942]" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" refId="ref26007" refString="Pringle ELL, Henning GA, Ball JB, editors. 1994. Pennington' s butterflies of southern Africa. 2 nd edn. Winchester: Struik." type="book" year="1994">Pringle et al. 1994</bibRefCitation>
, p.296), 
<taxonomicName id="85B7D18C36672268FD57FC4C869CFC38" baseAuthorityName="Godart" baseAuthorityYear="1819" box="[650,759,918,942]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Belenois" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gidica">
<emphasis id="70C3761D36672268FD57FC4C869CFC38" box="[650,759,918,942]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567">B. gidica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs throughout much of the Afrotropical Region, although it is absent from southwestern 
<collectingRegion id="807364ED36672268FC47FC6C8054FC58" box="[922,1087,950,974]" country="South Africa" name="Western Cape" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567">Cape Province</collectingRegion>
(
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F36672268FB8DFC6C8574FC7B" name="South Africa" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567">South Africa</collectingCountry>
), 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F36672268FEE9FC0F85A9FC7B" box="[308,450,981,1005]" name="Madagascar" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="3AA0EA9F36672268FE13FC0F8654FC7B" box="[462,575,981,1005]" name="Seychelles" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567">Seychelles</collectingCountry>
and the Mascarene Islands (
<bibRefCitation id="2626D7FE36672268FC54FC0F8030FC7B" author="Ackery PR &amp; Smith CR &amp; Vane-Wright RI" box="[905,1115,981,1005]" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567" refId="ref24360" refString="Ackery PR, Smith CR, Vane-Wright RI, editors. 1995. Carcasson' s African butterflies: an annotated catalogue of the Papilionoidea and Hesperioidea of the Afrotropical Region. East Melbourne (Australia): CSIRO." type="book" year="1995">Ackery et al. 1995</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4208AA0F36672268FF23FC2F8023FB5B" blockId="25.[212,1172,694,1229]" pageId="25" pageNumber="1567">On the upperside males are invariably white in ground colour, and relatively constant in pattern. On the hindwing underside, however, they are either white or yellowish-white with black markings, or largely suffused with mid-brown and divided by a long whitish fascia (dry-season f. “abyssinica”; intermediates occur). Females vary in upperside ground colour from white (male-like) through whitish-yellow to yellow, and vary greatly in the extent of the dark markings – rarely they are almost entirely infuscated. On the underside, females vary in the same way as males.</paragraph>
